Exploring My Commute: When, How, and How Often I Travel

I collected data about my commuting habits using a Google Form, where I recorded whether the day was a weekday or a weekend, which modes of public transport I used, and the time I logged my commute. The goal was to explore how my commute patterns change depending on the type of day and time.

The first plot shows a clear difference in frequency: I commute far more on weekdays than weekends, which aligns with my usual work schedule. To make the plot visually engaging, I used the cuttingshapes package to integrate a cat image into the bar chart — a fun way to present familiar data.

In the second plot , I broke down my transport modes using a bubble chart. Buses and trains appear more frequently on weekdays, while walking is more common on weekends. This suggests I stay local on weekends and rely on public transport mainly for weekday responsibilities.

Finally ( third plot ) , I visualised the timing of my commutes using a density plot. The two peaks — one around 8am and another around 5pm — match typical morning and evening commute times, confirming that my travel behavior is tied closely to a daily routine.

Through this project, I was able to turn everyday data into meaningful insights about my own behavior. The process also gave me a chance to combine visual storytelling with creativity and data skills — and of course, some cats.
